<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-343-192  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 343 192.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 12 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Software firm accuses Maryland agency of lying. (Lamarian SystemsInc. disputes Maryland Port Administration bidding rating)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lamarian Systems Inc. (cases).andO;Topic:     Software PublishersGovernment ContractsInvestigationsMaryland. Port AdministrationLegal IssuesCompetitive Bidding.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>SOFTWARE FIRM ACCUSES MARYLAND AGENCY OF LYING BALTIMORE, MARYLAND, U.S.A.,andO;1990 APR 11 (NB) -- Harry Latimer, president of Greenbelt, Maryland'sLamarian Systems Inc., has repeated to Newsbytes his accusations that theMaryland Port Administration (MPA) had improperly handled a computer contractbidding process and misrepresentated the method of bid evaluation.andM;Latimer's original statements, which appeared in Sunday's Baltimore Sun, saidthat the Agency had originally ranked his firm second in a bidding processfor the installation of software for the Agency's new Seagirt Marine Terminalbut, when the bid winner had to drop out, the ratings were revised andanother firm placed ahead of Lamarian.andP;  The same Sun article quoted MPAExecutive Director Brenden O'Malley as saying that state officials made thechanges in rankings after they factored in the ability to interface Seagirtcomputers with U.S.andP;  Customs Service computers in a system called ACROSS thatexchanges information on cargoes.andM;In his comments to Newsbytes, Latimer rejected O'Malley's statements saying:&quot;They don't make sense.andP;  The MPA brought us in on a sole source purchaseorder to design an interface to the ACROSS system because of our particularexpertise in this area.andP;  They can't say now that we don't have heavyexperience.andP;  They brought us in as a sole source contractor rather than gothrough the bidding process because of our experience.&quot; Latimer added,&quot;Itdidn't make sense from the beginning.andP;  We're a Maryland firm that provideslocal support in the event of problems while our competitor can't.andP;  We'vedone two projects successfully for the agency, one as a subcontractor toArthur Andersen.andP;  We have a proven record of success working in other portssuch as Oakland, CA and have strong recommendations from the Department ofTransportation.andP;  We're presently involved in major port projects inAustralia.andP;  And then they use a reason to defend the re-evaluation that'sobviously a lie.andP;  I just don't understand it.&quot;andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19900411)</TEXT></DOC>